There was a statistically-significant difference (p = 0.001) in patients’ discharge destinations, with an increase in the rate of hospital admissions in Period 4 (Table 1
). The rate of hospital admissions was 7.6% in Period 1, 6.3% in Period 2, 8.2% in Period 3, and 12.9% in Period 4. In all the four periods, osteoporotic hip fracture was the most common reason for hospital admissions. Moreover, the number of hospital admissions for osteoporotic hip fracture remained relatively stable throughout the four periods: 42 patients in Period 1, 41 in Period 2, 43 in Period 3 and 36 in Period 4 (p = 0.06) (Figure 2
).
